# Overview

This document runs a 56-run tetraploid GWAS pipeline on blackberry budbreak phenotypes
using `GWASpoly`. Manhattan plots below each run are loaded from pre-saved PNGs —
re-rendering this document does **not** re-run the GWAS analyses unless you explicitly
uncomment lines in the OPTIONAL block.

**Four GWAS blocks:**

| Block | Cohort      | Covariate              | Runs  |
|-------|-------------|------------------------|-------|
| A     | FFPF (all)  | PF status              | 1–14  |
| B     | FFPF (all)  | None (PF locus test)   | 15–28 |
| C     | FF only     | None                   | 29–42 |
| D     | PF only     | None                   | 43–56 |

**Traits per block (14 each):**
BIN_3Jan, BIN_15Jan, FRAC_3Jan, FRAC_15Jan, PERCENT_3Jan, PERCENT_15Jan,
BLUP_PERCENT_3Jan, BLUP_PERCENT_15Jan, BLUE_PERCENT_3Jan, BLUE_PERCENT_15Jan,
COMP_PERCENT, COMP_FRAC, PC1, PC2

## Biological Background

Blackberry budbreak timing is a quantitative trait governed by chilling hour accumulation over winter. Plants that have not received sufficient chilling remain dormant; those that have met their chilling requirement begin to break bud. In this experiment, canes were removed from field storage at two different chilling levels — approximately 200 chill hours (assessed 3-Jan) and approximately 263 chill hours (assessed 15-Jan) — and placed in a forcing environment. The proportion of buds that broke is the primary phenotype.

Primocane-fruiting (PF) genotypes carry a dominant allele at a single major locus that enables fruiting on first-year canes. This PF locus is known to be associated with budbreak phenotypes, so we must explicitly account for it — either statistically (as a covariate in Block A) or by cohort restriction (Blocks C and D) — to distinguish budbreak QTL that are independent of PF from those that are pleiotropic with it.

