# Phenotype Construction

## Load & Reshape CSV

The source phenotype file has an unusual structure: two completely separate experiments are laid out side-by-side in the same Excel sheet, separated by a blank column. The **left block** (columns 1–10) contains plants assessed at approximately 263 chill hours, with the primary observation date of 15-Jan. The **right block** (columns 12–21) contains a different set of plants assessed at approximately 200 chill hours, with the primary observation date of 3-Jan. The genotype in column 1 and the genotype in column 12 on any given row are **different plants** — they share a row purely because of Excel layout, not because of any biological relationship.

When `data.table::fread()` reads this file, it sees one flat 21-column table. The duplicate column names (`Lug Order`, `Total Buds`) are disambiguated by `make.unique()`, which appends `.1` to the second occurrence of each — so the right-side lug order becomes `Lug Order.1` and the right-side bud total becomes `Total Buds.1`. We then parse the left and right halves as completely separate data frames before computing any derived traits, so each phenotypic measurement is always associated with the correct genotype.

We also extract the **spatial block letter** (A, B, C, or D) from each lug ID at this stage using a regex lookahead. This letter identifies which physical block of the trial a plant was grown in — an important environmental covariate for the mixed models later. The regex `[A-Da-d](?=_\\d+$)` finds a block letter that is immediately followed by `_` and then the replicate digit at the end of the string, which uniquely identifies it among the other parts of the lug ID.

Finally, any row where `Total Buds` is zero or missing is removed before computing fractions. Division by zero would produce silent `NaN` values that would propagate invisibly through all downstream steps.

```{r load-reshape}
ph_raw <- .read_csv(pheno_file)
names(ph_raw) <- make.unique(names(ph_raw))  # disambiguates duplicate Excel headers

# ── Left block: ~263 chill hours, assessed 15-Jan ──────────────────────────
# Raw columns used: Lug Order (col 1), Total Buds (col 4), 15-Jan (col 6)
left_block <- ph_raw %>%
  select(
    LugOrder  = `Lug Order`,
    TotalBuds = `Total Buds`,
    Cnt_15Jan = `15-Jan`
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(LugOrder), LugOrder != "") %>%
  mutate(
    NAME      = get_name(LugOrder),
    # Spatial block letter extracted from lug ID for use in mixed models.
    # e.g. APF-665T_3_19_B_1 → Block = "B"
    Block     = stringr::str_extract(LugOrder, "[A-Da-d](?=_\\d+$)"),
    TotalBuds = suppressWarnings(as.numeric(TotalBuds)),
    Cnt_15Jan = .clamp_counts(Cnt_15Jan, TotalBuds)
  ) %>%
  # Remove rows with zero or missing Total Buds to prevent NaN in derived traits
  filter(!is.na(TotalBuds), TotalBuds > 0) %>%
  mutate(
    PERCENT_15Jan = 100 * Cnt_15Jan / TotalBuds,   # 0–100 scale
    FRAC_15Jan    = Cnt_15Jan / TotalBuds,          # 0–1 scale
    BIN_15Jan     = as.integer(Cnt_15Jan > 0)       # 1 = any budbreak, 0 = none
  )

# ── Right block: ~200 chill hours, assessed 3-Jan ──────────────────────────
# make.unique renamed duplicated headers: "Lug Order.1" and "Total Buds.1"
right_block <- ph_raw %>%
  select(
    LugOrder  = `Lug Order.1`,
    TotalBuds = `Total Buds.1`,
    Cnt_3Jan  = `3-Jan`
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(LugOrder), LugOrder != "") %>%
  mutate(
    NAME      = get_name(LugOrder),
    Block     = stringr::str_extract(LugOrder, "[A-Da-d](?=_\\d+$)"),
    TotalBuds = suppressWarnings(as.numeric(TotalBuds)),
    Cnt_3Jan  = .clamp_counts(Cnt_3Jan, TotalBuds)
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(TotalBuds), TotalBuds > 0) %>%
  mutate(
    PERCENT_3Jan = 100 * Cnt_3Jan / TotalBuds,
    FRAC_3Jan    = Cnt_3Jan / TotalBuds,
    BIN_3Jan     = as.integer(Cnt_3Jan > 0)
  )

cat("[RESHAPE] Left block rows :", nrow(left_block),
    "| Unique genotypes:", n_distinct(left_block$NAME), "\n")
cat("[RESHAPE] Right block rows:", nrow(right_block),
    "| Unique genotypes:", n_distinct(right_block$NAME), "\n")
```

## PF Assignment

Every genotype in the trial needs a PF status flag (1 = primocane-fruiting, 0 = floricane-fruiting) for two reasons. First, it is used as a **fixed-effect covariate** in Block A runs to statistically remove the variance attributable to the PF locus before testing all other markers. Second, it is used as a **cohort filter** in Blocks C and D: Block C restricts to PF=0 (FF-only), and Block D restricts to PF=1 (PF-only), removing any cross-background confounding entirely rather than relying on statistical control.

The naming convention in this population makes PF assignment straightforward for breeding lines: any genotype whose name starts with `APF` is a primocane-fruiting advanced line, and any genotype starting with `A-` is a floricane-fruiting advanced line. Named commercial varieties are assigned individually based on their known biology. Any genotype that falls through all conditions gets `PF = NA` and is flagged in the console — those individuals will be excluded from cohort-filtered runs (C and D) and will have their PF covariate missing in Block A runs. If any NA names appear, they should be added to the `case_when` block above before proceeding.

```{r pf-assignment}
all_names <- union(unique(left_block$NAME), unique(right_block$NAME))

PF_tbl <- tibble(NAME = all_names) %>%
  mutate(
    PF = case_when(
      # Breeding line prefixes — reliable naming convention
      startsWith(NAME, "APF")   ~ 1L,   # primocane-fruiting advanced lines
      startsWith(NAME, "A-")    ~ 0L,   # floricane-fruiting advanced lines
      # Named commercial varieties — assigned by known biology
      NAME %in% c(
        "PrimeArkFreedom",
        "PrimeArkHorizon",
        "Superlicious"
      )                         ~ 1L,   # confirmed PF commercial varieties
      NAME %in% c(
        "Osage", "Ouachita", "Natchez",
        "Apache", "Ponca", "Caddo",
        "Navaho", "Lochness", "Immaculate",
        "Von", "Tupy", "Stella"
      )                         ~ 0L,   # confirmed FF commercial varieties
      TRUE                      ~ NA_integer_  # unclassified — see warning below
    )
  )

cat("[PF] PF=1:", sum(PF_tbl$PF == 1, na.rm = TRUE),
    "| PF=0:", sum(PF_tbl$PF == 0, na.rm = TRUE),
    "| PF=NA:", sum(is.na(PF_tbl$PF)), "\n")

# Any name that reached NA is printed here for manual review
na_names <- PF_tbl %>% filter(is.na(PF)) %>% pull(NAME)
if (length(na_names) > 0) {
  cat("[PF WARNING] Unclassified genotypes (PF=NA) — add to case_when above:\n")
  print(na_names)
}
```

## BLUP / BLUE Models

Raw budbreak percentages contain both true genetic signal and noise from the field environment — specifically, spatial variation across the physical blocks of the trial. A plant in a sheltered block may have accumulated chill hours slightly differently from one in an exposed block. To separate these effects we fit a mixed model for each trait before passing phenotypes to GWASpoly.

**BLUP (Best Linear Unbiased Prediction)** treats genotype as a **random effect**. The model is:

```
trait ~ Block + (1|NAME)
```

Here `Block` is the spatial block letter (A/B/C/D) as a fixed effect, capturing systematic environmental differences between blocks. `(1|NAME)` is the genotype random effect — the per-genotype deviation from the population mean after accounting for block. The BLUP value for each genotype is this random effect estimate: it is a **shrinkage estimator**, meaning genotypes with fewer replicates or noisier data are shrunk toward the population mean. This makes BLUPs conservative but stable across unbalanced designs.

**BLUE (Best Linear Unbiased Estimate)** treats genotype as a **fixed effect**. The model is:

```
trait ~ Block + NAME
```

The BLUE for each genotype is the corresponding regression coefficient — the estimated genotype mean conditional on block. Unlike BLUPs, BLUEs are not shrunk toward the population mean, so they are more sensitive to sparse data but also more powerful when data is abundant and balanced.

We fit both estimators and carry both through to GWAS as separate traits. If a model fails to converge (e.g., because the trait has very little variance within a block), the fallback is raw genotype means — a valid if less precise alternative.

The `lmerControl(optimizer = "bobyqa")` setting tells `lme4` to use the BOBYQA numerical optimizer with an increased iteration budget (`maxfun = 1e5`). The default optimizer sometimes fails to converge on phenotypic data with skewed distributions like budbreak fractions; BOBYQA is more robust in practice for this type of data.

```{r blup-blue}
mk_blup_blue <- function(df, trait) {

  message("[BLUP/BLUE] Processing: ", trait)

  df <- df %>%
    filter(!is.na(.data[[trait]]), is.finite(.data[[trait]]))

  # Safety check: skip if there's not enough data to fit a meaningful model
  if (nrow(df) < 10 || n_distinct(df$NAME) < 3) {
    message("[SKIP] Not enough data for ", trait)
    fallback <- df %>%
      group_by(NAME) %>%
      summarise(
        !!paste0("BLUE_", trait) := mean(.data[[trait]], na.rm = TRUE),
        !!paste0("BLUP_", trait) := mean(.data[[trait]], na.rm = TRUE),
        .groups = "drop"
      )
    return(list(
      BLUP = fallback %>% select(NAME, paste0("BLUP_", trait)),
      BLUE = fallback %>% select(NAME, paste0("BLUE_", trait))
    ))
  }

  # Convert NAME and Block to factors so lme4 treats them as categorical variables.
  # Block must be a factor (not a character string) for the fixed-effect contrast
  # coding to work correctly in both lmer and lm.
  df$NAME  <- factor(df$NAME)
  df$Block <- factor(df$Block)

  # ── BLUP: genotype as random effect, block as fixed ───────────────────────
  # REML=TRUE is the standard for random-effects estimation (vs ML used for
  # fixed-effect testing). BOBYQA optimizer is more robust for bounded phenotypes.
  blups_tbl <- tryCatch({
    m1 <- lmer(
      as.formula(paste0(trait, " ~ Block + (1|NAME)")),
      data    = df,
      REML    = TRUE,
      control = lmerControl(optimizer = "bobyqa",
                            optCtrl   = list(maxfun = 1e5))
    )
    re <- ranef(m1)$NAME   # extract genotype random effects
    tibble(
      NAME                      = rownames(re),
      !!paste0("BLUP_", trait) := as.numeric(re[, "(Intercept)"])
    )
  }, error = function(e) {
    message("[BLUP FAIL] Using genotype means for ", trait, " — ", conditionMessage(e))
    df %>%
      group_by(NAME) %>%
      summarise(!!paste0("BLUP_", trait) := mean(.data[[trait]], na.rm = TRUE),
                .groups = "drop")
  })

  # ── BLUE: genotype as fixed effect, block as fixed ────────────────────────
  # Coefficients with "NAME" prefix are the per-genotype fixed effects.
  # Note: the intercept represents the reference genotype (first level of NAME
  # factor), so all other coefficients are relative contrasts. This is standard
  # treatment contrast coding in R's lm().
  blues_tbl <- tryCatch({
    m2  <- lm(as.formula(paste0(trait, " ~ Block + NAME")), df)
    co  <- coef(m2)
    val <- co[grepl("^NAME", names(co))]
    tibble(
      NAME                      = gsub("^NAME", "", names(val)),
      !!paste0("BLUE_", trait) := as.numeric(val)
    )
  }, error = function(e) {
    message("[BLUE FAIL] Using genotype means for ", trait, " — ", conditionMessage(e))
    df %>%
      group_by(NAME) %>%
      summarise(!!paste0("BLUE_", trait) := mean(.data[[trait]], na.rm = TRUE),
                .groups = "drop")
  })

  list(BLUP = blups_tbl, BLUE = blues_tbl)
}

# Run models separately for each chill-hour block.
# The left block (263h) provides PERCENT_15Jan phenotypes.
# The right block (200h) provides PERCENT_3Jan phenotypes.
bb3  <- mk_blup_blue(right_block, "PERCENT_3Jan")
bb15 <- mk_blup_blue(left_block,  "PERCENT_15Jan")
```

## Composite Traits

The two chill-hour treatments (200h and 263h) represent different points along the same biological response curve — the chilling requirement of each genotype. A genotype with a low chilling requirement will show high budbreak at both timepoints; one with a high requirement will show low budbreak at 200h but may catch up by 263h.

Averaging the two timepoints into a single composite score collapses this two-dimensional phenotype into one number that captures overall chilling responsiveness across the range of conditions tested. This is useful as a GWAS trait because it increases power to detect QTL that influence chilling requirement globally, at the cost of losing the ability to detect QTL that specifically affect one chill level but not the other (which the individual-timepoint traits will catch).

The join on `NAME` here is critical — we must ensure that the 3-Jan observation and the 15-Jan observation being averaged belong to the same genotype, not to different plants that happened to share a row in the Excel file.

```{r composite-traits}
# Per-genotype mean traits from each block
left_means <- left_block %>%
  group_by(NAME) %>%
  summarise(across(c(BIN_15Jan, FRAC_15Jan, PERCENT_15Jan),
                   \(x) mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)),
            .groups = "drop")

right_means <- right_block %>%
  group_by(NAME) %>%
  summarise(across(c(BIN_3Jan, FRAC_3Jan, PERCENT_3Jan),
                   \(x) mean(x, na.rm = TRUE)),
            .groups = "drop")

# full_join preserves all genotypes even if one block has missing data for them
COMP_tbl <- full_join(left_means, right_means, by = "NAME") %>%
  mutate(
    # rowMeans with na.rm=TRUE means a genotype present in only one block still
    # gets a composite score (equal to its single-block value), rather than NA
    COMP_PERCENT = rowMeans(cbind(PERCENT_3Jan, PERCENT_15Jan), na.rm = TRUE),
    COMP_FRAC    = rowMeans(cbind(FRAC_3Jan,    FRAC_15Jan),    na.rm = TRUE)
  )
```

## Phenotypic PCA (PC1 & PC2 Traits)

Principal Component Analysis is applied here to the matrix of per-genotype budbreak trait means. This is a **phenotypic PCA** — it finds the directions of maximum variance in the phenotype space, not in the genome. The resulting PC scores are then used as GWAS traits in runs 13/14, 27/28, 41/42, and 55/56.

The motivation is that individual budbreak traits are highly correlated with each other (a genotype that breaks many buds at 3-Jan also tends to break many at 15-Jan). Testing each trait separately is statistically valid, but GWAS power is spread across correlated phenotypes. A QTL that influences the overall budbreak axis may appear as a modest signal in each individual trait, but as a strong signal in the PC1 score that captures that axis. Conversely, a QTL that specifically governs the *contrast* between early and late budbreak — i.e., the timing of budbreak onset rather than its magnitude — may only appear in PC2.

**Important:** this PCA does not replace the kinship-based population structure correction inside GWASpoly. The PC scores are phenotypes being mapped, not genomic PCs being used as covariates. GWASpoly handles population structure separately via the kinship matrix computed with `set.K()`.

All four input traits (PERCENT_3Jan, PERCENT_15Jan, FRAC_3Jan, FRAC_15Jan) are scaled to unit variance before PCA so that no single trait dominates the axes due to scale differences (PERCENT is on a 0–100 scale; FRAC is on 0–1). After scaling, `prcomp()` with `center=FALSE, scale.=FALSE` is used because centering and scaling were already applied manually.

```{r pca-phenotypic}
# Input matrix: per-genotype means of four correlated budbreak traits
# complete.cases() required because prcomp cannot handle missing values
pca_input <- COMP_tbl %>%
  select(NAME, PERCENT_3Jan, PERCENT_15Jan, FRAC_3Jan, FRAC_15Jan) %>%
  filter(complete.cases(.))

# scale() centers each column to mean=0 and scales to sd=1
# This prevents PERCENT (0–100) from dominating over FRAC (0–1)
pca_mat <- pca_input %>%
  select(-NAME) %>%
  scale()

# prcomp performs singular value decomposition of the scaled matrix
# center=FALSE and scale.=FALSE because we already did both above
pca_res <- prcomp(pca_mat, center = FALSE, scale. = FALSE)

# PC scores: each row is one genotype, columns are PC1 and PC2
pca_scores <- tibble(
  NAME = pca_input$NAME,
  PC1  = pca_res$x[, 1],   # largest variance axis — overall budbreak responsiveness
  PC2  = pca_res$x[, 2]    # second axis — early vs. late budbreak contrast
)

# Report variance explained — if PC1 < 50%, the "single axis" interpretation weakens
var_exp <- summary(pca_res)$importance["Proportion of Variance", ]
cat("[PCA] PC1 variance explained:", round(var_exp[1] * 100, 1), "%\n")
cat("[PCA] PC2 variance explained:", round(var_exp[2] * 100, 1), "%\n")
cat("[PCA] Genotypes included    :", nrow(pca_scores), "\n")
```

## Master Phenotype Table

All derived traits — raw group means, BLUP-adjusted values, BLUE-adjusted values, composite scores, PC scores, and PF status — are assembled into a single wide table called `PH_MASTER`. This is the single source of truth for all downstream GWAS runs. Each row is one unique genotype (one `NAME`). The `left_join` operations mean that any genotype missing from a particular estimator (e.g., too few observations for BLUP) will have `NA` for that trait column, and the per-run GWAS function will skip that run gracefully if too few non-missing values remain.

```{r master-phenotype}
PH_MASTER <- COMP_tbl %>%
  left_join(bb3$BLUP,   by = "NAME") %>%   # BLUP for PERCENT_3Jan
  left_join(bb15$BLUP,  by = "NAME") %>%   # BLUP for PERCENT_15Jan
  left_join(bb3$BLUE,   by = "NAME") %>%   # BLUE for PERCENT_3Jan
  left_join(bb15$BLUE,  by = "NAME") %>%   # BLUE for PERCENT_15Jan
  left_join(pca_scores, by = "NAME") %>%   # PC1 and PC2 from phenotypic PCA
  left_join(PF_tbl,     by = "NAME")       # PF status (0/1/NA)

cat("[PH_MASTER] Rows:", nrow(PH_MASTER),
    "| Columns:", ncol(PH_MASTER), "\n")
glimpse(PH_MASTER)
```

